=== Memoir ===
In June 2010, Benatar's memoir, ''Between a Heart and a Rock Place'', was released.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Benatar |first=Pat |title=Between a Heart and a Rock Place: A Memoir |date=June 15, 2010 |publisher=HarperCollins |isbn=978-0-06-195377-4 |author-link=Pat Benatar}}</ref> The book was published by [[HarperCollins]] and was acquired by Lisa Sharkey. Benatar's memoir touches on her battles with her record company Chrysalis, the difficulties that her career caused in her personal life, and feminism. In the memoir, she is quoted as saying, "For every day since I was old enough to think, I've considered myself a feminist … It's empowering to watch and to know that, perhaps in some way, I made the hard path [women] have to walk just a little bit easier."<ref>{{cite web|last=Eby|first=Margaret|date=June 18, 2010|title=10 best moments from Pat Benatar's memoir|url=https://www.salon.com/2010/06/18/best_parts_of_pat_benatars_memoir/|url-status=live|access-date=June 16, 2013|website=Salon}}</ref> The book went on to become a [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' bestseller]]. Initially reluctant to undertake the project, she found the actual writing process so enjoyable that it inspired her with plans to write a novel.<ref name="NewsdayMemoir">{{Cite news |date=June 14, 2010 |title=Pat Benatar takes her best shot in new book |work=Newsday |url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/pat-benatar-takes-her-best-shot-in-new-book-1.2021868 |access-date=April 24, 2014}}</ref> In summer 2011, Benatar announced she was working on a Christmas album and a novel about the [[Second Coming|second coming of Christ]].<ref name="PatBenatarChristmas">{{Cite magazine |date=September 14, 2009 |title=Pat Benatar Plans Christmas Album, Jesus Christ Novel |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/469191/pat-benatar-plans-christmas-album-jesus-christ-novel |access-date=March 31, 2012 |magazine=Billboard}}</ref>

== Band ==
Although billed as a solo artist, Benatar recorded and toured with a consistent set of band members over most of her career:
* [[Neil Giraldo|Neil "Spyder" Giraldo]] (incorrectly spelled as "Geraldo" in early liner notes/credits) is the lead guitarist of the band and has performed on all of Benatar's albums.
* Myron Grombacher, who played with Giraldo in Rick Derringer's touring band, is drummer on nine of Benatar's original albums (''[[Crimes of Passion (Pat Benatar album)|Crimes of Passion]]'', ''[[Precious Time (album)|Precious Time]]'', ''[[Get Nervous]]'', ''[[Live from Earth]]'', ''[[Tropico (Pat Benatar album)|Tropico]]'', ''[[Seven the Hard Way]]'', ''[[Wide Awake in Dreamland]]'', ''[[True Love (Pat Benatar album)|True Love]]'', and ''[[Gravity's Rainbow (album)|Gravity's Rainbow]]'') and has numerous writing credits. Grombacher is easily recognizable in the music videos, particularly as the mad dentist in "Anxiety (Get Nervous)".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://remo.com/team/member/myron-grombacher/|title=Myron Grombacher|website=Remo.com|access-date=July 15, 2021}}</ref>
* [[Charlie Giordano]] performed keyboard duties on six albums (''[[Get Nervous]]'', ''[[Live from Earth]]'', ''[[Tropico (Pat Benatar album)|Tropico]]'', ''[[Seven the Hard Way]]'', ''[[Wide Awake in Dreamland]]'' and ''[[True Love (Pat Benatar album)|True Love]]'') and is identifiable by his glasses and distinctive array of berets, blazers, and 1980s-style ties. In 2007, he replaced the late [[Danny Federici]] in the [[E Street Band]].
* Roger Capps, the original bassist for the first five albums (''[[In the Heat of the Night (Pat Benatar album)|In the Heat of the Night]]'', ''[[Crimes of Passion (Pat Benatar album)|Crimes of Passion]]'', ''[[Precious Time (album)|Precious Time]]'', ''[[Get Nervous]]'', and ''[[Live from Earth]]''), co-wrote "[[Hell Is For Children]]" with Benatar and Giraldo and left the band in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://webelongtribute.com/roger-capps|title=We Belong – Roger Capps|website=Webelongtribute.com|access-date=July 15, 2021}}</ref>
*[[Scott St. Clair Sheets]] (Scott Sheets) who was originally the lead guitarist of the 1970s band, The Brats, was an original member of the Pat Benatar Band. Sheets is credited as guitarist on the first three albums (''[[In the Heat of the Night (Pat Benatar album)|In the Heat of the Night]]'', ''[[Crimes of Passion (Pat Benatar album)|Crimes of Passion]]'', and ''[[Precious Time (album)|Precious Time]]'') and first three world tours. He wrote the song "Prisoner of Love" for the ''Crimes of Passion'' album and co-wrote the hit "Fire and Ice" for the ''Precious Time'' album. 
* Mick Mahan is the band's bassist and has performed with Benatar since 1995 and has appeared on albums (''[[Innamorata (album)|Innamorata]]'' and ''[[Go (Pat Benatar album)|Go]]''). The original bassist, Roger Capps, was replaced by Donnie Nossov on ''Tropico'', and then later by Frank Linx.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mickmahan.com/bio/|title = Biography &#124; Mick Mahan|website=Mickmahan.com}}</ref>
* Donnie Nossov was the band's second bassist for two of Pat Benatar's albums (''[[Tropico (Pat Benatar album)|Tropico]]'' and ''[[Seven the Hard Way]]'') 
* Frank Linx was the bassist for two of Pat Benatar's studio albums (''[[Wide Awake in Dreamland]]'' and ''[[Gravity's Rainbow (album)|Gravity's Rainbow]]'')
* Glen Alexander Hamilton played drums on the first album (''[[In the Heat of the Night (Pat Benatar album)|In the Heat of the Night]]'').
* [[Chuck Domanico]] was the band's bassist on their eighth studio album and ninth album overall (''[[True Love (Pat Benatar album)|True Love]]'')
* Chris Ralles is the band's current drummer.

== Stage and screen appearances ==
[[File:NeilGiraldowithPatBenatarLiveinSydney.jpg|right|thumb|Benatar and Giraldo, October 2010]]
* Benatar played the role of Jeanette Florescu in the film [[Union City (film)|''Union City'']] (1980), directed by [[Marcus Reichert|Mark Reichert]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Union City |url=https://catalog.afi.com/Film/56712-UNION-CITY#1 |access-date=July 13, 2020 |website=American Film Institute catalog}}</ref>
* Benatar played the character Zephyr in [[Harry Chapin]]'s futuristic rock musical ''The Zinger''. Benatar performed the solo "Shooting Star" in honor of Chapin for the Harry Chapin Tribute, Carnegie Hall, December 7, 1987.
* Benatar has made numerous television appearances, mostly as herself. She appeared with her husband Neil Giraldo in the ''[[Charmed]]'' episode "[[Lucky Charmed]]" on which "[[Heartbreaker (Pat Benatar song)|Heartbreaker]]" was used and in an episode of ''[[Dharma & Greg]]'' as herself singing "We've Only Just Begun" at an impromptu wedding in an airport. In 2001, she also appeared as fictional rock star Anna Raines in the CBS television drama ''[[Family Law (American TV series)|Family Law]]'' with Dixie Carter and Christopher McDonald. Benatar also appeared on ''[[That 80's Show]]'' as herself.
* Benatar appeared as a special guest at the sixth annual ''[[VH1 Divas]]'' concert, ''VH1 Divas Duets'', performing "Heartbreaker" with Giraldo and headliner [[Lisa Marie Presley]], with the married couple interviewed by [[Sharon Osbourne]] following the performance.
* In 2003, Benatar and her music were featured on ''[[CMT Crossroads]]'', in an episode that paired her with country singer [[Martina McBride]] (who was influenced by Benatar's vocal range).
* Benatar and Giraldo performed in the [[Tiny Desk Concerts]] series of [[NPR Music]] on November 14, 2014. At the Tiny Desk, Benatar and Giraldo ran through three of their classic songs: "We Live For Love," "We Belong" and "Promises In The Dark".<ref>{{cite web |date=November 14, 2014 |title=Pat Benatar & Neil Giraldo |url=https://www.npr.org/event/music/364721657/pat-benatar-neil-giraldo-tiny-desk-concert |access-date=March 6, 2017 |website=[[NPR Music]]}}</ref>

